A FAIR data product's signing & trust lifecycle, through four hands. Runs the real `tessera` binary
against a fixture `study.tsra` (a sealed recon product, as if freshly acquired). Random key material is
globbed with `[..]`; everything else is the verbatim transcript.

# === Instrument scientist — generate a signing key, sign the study at the source (air-gapped OK). ===

```
$ tessera keygen instrument.key
wrote private key instrument.key (keep secret — mode 0600)
wrote public  key instrument.key.pub (share freely)
  key_id [..]

```

```
$ tessera sign study.tsra --key instrument.key --signer https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1825-0097
OK  signed study.tsra
  sidecar   study.tsra.sig.json
  key_id    [..]
  key_fmt   raw-hex
  signed_at [..]
  signer    https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1825-0097

```

# === Data scientist — refuses an unknown key: untrusted until the custodian vets it. ===

```
$ tessera verify-sig study.tsra
? failed
error: [..]untrusted: key_id [..]is not in the trust store[..]

```

# === Data custodian — vets + trusts the instrument's key (repo-local store); now it verifies. ===

```
$ tessera trust add instrument.key.pub --name instrument-lab --signer https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1825-0097 --repo
trusted 'instrument-lab'  key_id [..]  signer https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1825-0097

```

```
$ tessera trust list
instrument-lab   [..]  https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1825-0097

```

```
$ tessera verify-sig study.tsra
OK  study.tsra — trusted as 'instrument-lab' + 1 blocks intact
  signer https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1825-0097 (attribution; not a trust anchor)

```

# === Researcher / auditor — a signer-policy mismatch is rejected (attribution is checked too). ===

```
$ tessera verify-sig study.tsra --require-signer https://orcid.org/9999-9999-9999-9999
? failed
error: [..]signer policy: required 'https://orcid.org/9999-9999-9999-9999'[..]

```
